Using PBSzeros ensures we completely remove entire drug categories that are never prescribed.

# Any missing values in the Scripts column are replaced with 0.
PBS <- PBS |>
  fill_gaps(Scripts=0, .full=TRUE)

# Find series that are only 0s and exclude them.
PBSzeros <- PBS |>
  as_tibble() |>
  # Analyze each drug category separately.
  group_by(ATC1, ATC2, Concession, Type) |>
  # If all Scripts values for a drug category are 0 across all time periods, mean(abs(Scripts)) will also be 0.
  summarise(mas = mean(abs(Scripts))) |>
  # Keeps only those groups where Scripts was always 0.
  filter(mas==0)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'ATC1', 'ATC2', 'Concession'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
# Removes any drug categories that were always 0, ensuring that only meaningful prescription data remains.
PBS <- PBS |>
  anti_join(PBSzeros)
## Joining with `by = join_by(Concession, Type, ATC1, ATC2)`
print(PBS)

# aggregate_key() aggregates data across different hierarchical levels in the dataset.
# Sum all Scripts for each ATC1
# Sum Scripts within each ATC2 level for a given ATC1
# Within each ATC1/ATC2, it further sums Scripts by Concession and Type.

PBS_gts<- PBS |>
  aggregate_key(ATC1/ATC2 * Concession * Type, Scripts = sum(Scripts))
print(PBS_gts)

Plot Aggregated Scripts by ATC1

# The line plot shows the total Scripts for each ATC1 category over time.
# Keeps only rows where Concession, Type, and ATC2 are fully aggregated.
# This results in ATC1-level total prescription data.

PBS_gts %>%
  # The dataset is now aggregated only at the ATC1 level (higher-level classification of drugs), summing Scripts across ATC2, Concession, and Type.
  filter(is_aggregated(Concession), is_aggregated(Type),
         is_aggregated(ATC2)) %>%
  autoplot(Scripts)+
  labs(title = "PBS Aggregate Plot by ATC1") +
  theme(plot.margin = margin(0.1, 0.2, 0.1, 0.2, "cm"))  # Expands margins

Plot Aggregated Scripts by ATC1 (ATC2 Breakdown)

# The dataset now contains ATC2-level prescription data, while Concession and Type are fully aggregated.
# Each ATC1 drug classification gets its own subplot, displaying ATC2-level trends.
# ATC2 prescription trends are shown inside each ATC1 panel.
# Analyze prescription trends across different drug classes (ATC1) while maintaining ATC2-level details.
# Time Series of Total Scripts by ATC1 (ATC2 Breakdown, Aggregated Concession & Type)

PBS_gts %>%
  filter(is_aggregated(Concession), is_aggregated(Type),
         !is_aggregated(ATC1)) %>%
  autoplot(Scripts) +
  facet_wrap(vars(ATC1), scales = "free_y", ncol = 3) +
  labs(y = "Total Scripts", 
       title = "Total Scripts for ATC2 Categories, Grouped by ATC1") +
  theme(legend.position =  "none")

The top line is the total prescription volume for Concessional. The smaller lines are subcategories (ATC1/ATC2) contributing to that total. The patterns show seasonality and trends, with some categories contributing significantly more than others.

forecast_ets_base %>%
  filter(is_aggregated(Type)) %>%  # Keep it aggregated only by Type, not by Concession
  autoplot(
    PBS_gts %>% filter(year(Month) >= 2005),
    level = NULL
  ) +
  labs(y = "Count", title = "ETS Base Model to Forecast 36 Months") +
  facet_wrap(vars(Concession), scales = "free_y")  # Now it should work!

forecast_ets_base %>%
  accuracy(PBS_gts, measures = list(rmsse = RMSSE, mase = MASE)) %>%
  # After calculating RMSSE and MASE for each individual time series, it takes the mean across all series to provide an overall performance summary for each model (Mint_ets vs. ets).
  group_by(.model) %>%
  summarise(rmsse = mean(rmsse), mase = mean(mase))

c.Reconcile each of the forecasts using MinT.

ETS model with MinT Forecast Method

forecast_ets_base = Base forecasts at original levels.

forecast_ets_mint_36 = Base + reconciled forecasts, leading to twice as many rows.

ets_mint_model <-
  ets_base %>%
  reconcile(Mint_ets = min_trace(ets))
  
forecast_ets_mint_36 <- 
  forecast(ets_mint_model, h = "3 years")

print(forecast_ets_mint_36)

d.Which type of model works best on the test set?

To identify the best model, we compare RMSSE and MASE, where lower values indicate better accuracy. After reconciliation, the ARIMA model achieves the lowest RMSSE (2.34) and MASE (2.55), making it the best performer on the test set.The reconciled ARIMA model is best overall.

combined_model_results <- bind_rows(
  forecast_ets_mint_36 %>%
    accuracy(PBS_gts, measures = list(rmsse = RMSSE, mase = MASE)) %>%
    group_by(.model) %>%
    summarise(rmsse = mean(rmsse), mase = mean(mase)) %>%
    mutate(method = "ETS"),
  
  forecast_arima_mint_36 %>%
    accuracy(PBS_gts, measures = list(rmsse = RMSSE, mase = MASE)) %>%
    group_by(.model) %>%
    summarise(rmsse = mean(rmsse), mase = mean(mase)) %>%
    mutate(method = "ARIMA"),
  
  forecast_snaive_mint_36 %>%
    accuracy(PBS_gts, measures = list(rmsse = RMSSE, mase = MASE)) %>%
    group_by(.model) %>%
    summarise(rmsse = mean(rmsse), mase = mean(mase)) %>%
    mutate(method = "SNAIVE")
)

print(combined_model_results)

e. Does the reconciliation improve the forecast accuracy?

MinT reconciliation improves forecast accuracy by ensuring coherence across hierarchical levels. Comparing reconciled (Mint_) and non-reconciled models, ETS and ARIMA show lower RMSSE and MASE after reconciliation, confirming its effectiveness. However, for SNAIVE, reconciliation has no impact, as RMSSE and MASE remain unchanged. The reconciled ARIMA model is best overall.

Reconciliation aligns forecasts across hierarchical levels, reducing inconsistencies.
Forecast errors decrease because the model now uses more stable aggregate information, avoiding extreme fluctuations.
RMSSE and MASE improve (decrease) because the reconciled forecasts are more accurate relative to historical patterns.

f.Why doesnt the reconciliation make any difference to the SNAIVE forecasts?

The SNAIVE (Seasonal Naive) model forecasts using the last observed seasonal value without model estimation. Since it relies solely on raw data, reconciliation does not affect its forecasts, as there are no parameters to adjust or hierarchical inconsistencies to correct.
